controller suitable for hard kinds of bodies. And so in between what happens is during this process, the brain is largely, largely destroyed, most of the connections are broken down, most of the cells die, and and the new brain is rebuilt during the lifetime of the organism.

07:51.500 --> 08:03.500
And so, you know, this this this kind of change makes the confusion of puberty seem like real child's play, you know, in the sense that this is a single agent radically changing its its its brain and its body.

08:03.500 --> 08:17.500
And the amazing thing about it is that memories that the caterpillar acquires are retained in the moth or butterfly. So this has been shown so despite the despite the disaggregation of the brain actually some information is able to make it across.

08:17.500 --> 08:29.500
This can be even more radical these are these are planaria. These are flatworms and you'll see a lot more about them in this talk. The planaria regenerate any part of their body so you cut them into pieces. The record is something like 275 pieces.

08:29.500 --> 08:45.500
Each piece regrows exactly what's missing including the brain and you get perfect little worms. So, James McConnell back in the 60s, made an observation and it was, you know, quite controversial at the time but we repeated it and actually discovered he was he was absolutely right.

08:45.500 --> 08:55.500
What happens is that if you if you train these planaria to recognize a particular region of their environment, let's say one with these little little bumps laser etched into it as the place where they get fed.

08:55.500 --> 09:05.500
You can then amputate the head and the brain. I mean, these animals have a true centralized brain. Amputate the head and the brain leave the tail. The tail sits there for eight or nine days doing pretty much nothing.

09:05.500 --> 09:15.500
Eventually it grows a new fresh brain and somehow that information is imprinted onto this new brain and these animals show retention of that memory.

09:15.500 --> 09:24.500
So the information moving through the body being imprinted from one tissue onto another is something that we really need to start to understand.

09:24.500 --> 09:33.500
And in fact, beyond beyond those kind of experiments, you can do this invertebrates. We did this in the tadpole. So this is a tadpole of the frogs and a Peslevis.

09:33.500 --> 09:41.500
Here's the brain. Here are the nostrils. Here's the mouth, the gut and the tail. One thing you'll notice is that what we've done is we've prevented the normal eyes from forming.

09:41.500 --> 09:46.500
We've put an ectopic eye on the tail. So this is a this is an eye that forms on the tail.

09:46.500 --> 09:56.500
And the amazing thing about these animals is that with no long, in fact, with no period of evolutionary adaptation to this new configuration, they can see perfectly well out of these eyes.

09:56.500 --> 10:02.500
So we've made a device that tests them on visual training cues and sort of automates the same thing we use to test the planarian memory.

10:02.500 --> 10:12.500
It's an automated behavior testing device. And what we found is that this eye finds itself in a completely novel environment surrounding my muscle instead of near the brain, puts out an optic nerve.

10:12.500 --> 10:24.500
The optic nerve might connect to the spinal cord. It does not go up to the brain. The brain that evolved for tracking visual data from these two locations suddenly gets information from some weird itchy patch of tissue on its tail.

10:24.500 --> 10:30.500
No problem. It recognizes that as visual data and these animals behave quite well in learning assays.

10:30.500 --> 10:40.500
So navigating your world with a radically different configuration of sensory and processing organs.

10:40.500 --> 10:51.500
So what we really see in biology is that not only are we nested all structurally, I mean, we all, everyone knows that groups consist of individuals made of organs, tissues, cells and so on.

10:51.500 --> 10:59.500
But actually, each one of these levels has competency. It solves problems in its own space and there are lots of different kinds of spaces.

10:59.500 --> 11:14.500
And that multi-scale architecture, which is kind of unique, it's something that in engineering we're still really not able to recapitulate, although we're getting there, shows competency in many, many different spaces.

11:14.500 --> 11:23.500
Now, the one thing I'd like to do fundamentally is to generalize this idea of being able to perform intelligently in some space.

11:23.500 --> 11:32.500
So typically, we think about three-dimensional spaces. So behavior, moving the body in three-dimensional space.

11:32.500 --> 11:39.500
So it's very easy for us to recognize intelligence in those spaces because all of our sense organs point outward.

11:39.500 --> 11:47.500
And from the time you were very little, you were collecting data on medium-sized objects moving at medium speeds around you in three-dimensional space.

11:47.500 --> 11:52.500
And we know how to recognize birds and mammals and other things behaving intelligently.

11:52.500 --> 12:01.500
What we don't have are senses that directly show us, for example, imagine that you were born with a sense that where you could actually feel your blood chemistry,

12:01.500 --> 12:07.500
all the different things going on in your blood physiology and all of the things that your liver, pancreas and other organs were doing.

12:07.500 --> 12:13.500
In that case, we would have a training set that would allow us to understand intelligent navigation of other spaces.

12:13.500 --> 12:18.500
So that would be physiological space, so the space of physiological parameters.

12:18.500 --> 12:24.500
It might be a transcriptional space, so the space of gene expression, all the different gene expression domains,

12:24.500 --> 12:30.500
or in fact, morpho space, the space of all possible anatomical configurations. We'll talk more about that.

12:30.500 --> 12:42.500
I want to show you, and the fact that we're not familiar with these other spaces means that when we make claims about the cognitive level or the intelligence level of other systems,

12:42.500 --> 12:44.500
we're really taking an IQ test ourselves.

12:44.500 --> 12:47.500
What we're really saying is this is what we've recognized the system to be doing,

12:47.500 --> 12:54.500
but we can't really assume that we're smart enough to know exactly what it's doing and what it's solving in all of the different spaces.

12:54.500 --> 13:03.500
I want to show you a simple example. Again, these are the planaria, and what we found is that if we put planaria into a solution of barium chloride,

13:03.500 --> 13:10.500
so barium is a non-specific potassium channel blocker. It prevents these cells from exchanging potassium with the outside world.

13:10.500 --> 13:15.500
When you do this, literally their heads explode. Their heads just overnight they blow up.

13:15.500 --> 13:23.500
The amazing thing is that if you keep the rest of the worm in barium over the next couple of weeks, they regenerate, they grow a brand new head,

13:23.500 --> 13:28.500
and the new head does not care about barium whatsoever. The new head is barium adapted. That's kind of amazing.

13:28.500 --> 13:34.500
We asked a simple question. We just looked at the transcriptomes of naive worms versus barium adapted heads,

13:34.500 --> 13:39.500
and we just asked, well, what gene expression is different? What's different about these barium adapted heads?

13:39.500 --> 13:45.500
One thing we found is that there's only a handful of genes. There's less than a dozen genes that are in fact different,

13:45.500 --> 13:54.500
and so this system is able to figure out which genes to up and down regulate so that it can do its business without being able to pass potassium properly.

13:54.500 --> 13:59.500
But the incredible thing about this is that barium is not anything that planaria ever see in the wild.

13:59.500 --> 14:09.500
This is a completely unnatural novel stressor. So it's implausible to think that at some point there was evolutionary pressure to develop a response to barium.

14:09.500 --> 14:16.500
So what you're really talking about here is you're in the space of gene expression, which is, let's say if they have 20,000 genes,

14:16.500 --> 14:27.500
it's a massively very high dimensional space, and you need to walk in that space to find the exact genes that are going to solve your physiological stressor.

14:27.500 --> 14:37.500
Now, you don't have time to sort of randomly flip genes on and off, first of all, because it'll most likely kill you before you find the good combinations.

14:37.500 --> 14:43.500
Also, there's no time for that. These cells don't turn over that fast. It's not like a bacterial evolutionary system.

14:43.500 --> 14:51.500
So it's still very much an open question. How do they navigate this transcriptional space to solve these kinds of problems?

14:51.500 --> 14:59.500
So this to me is very much an example of intelligence in the sense of problem solving, taking what you already might know.

14:59.500 --> 15:06.500
Maybe there's information about what to do in a case of epileptic seizures or so on, and bringing it to a new scenario.

15:06.500 --> 15:14.500
And so I've been working on this framework. It's called TAME. It stands for technological approach to mind everywhere.

15:14.500 --> 15:21.500
And the goal of this framework is to be able to recognize, create, and relate to truly diverse intelligences.

15:21.500 --> 15:30.500
So we need to handle, of course, the things we're familiar with, birds, primates, and so on, but also weird colonial organisms and swarms and things like that.

15:30.500 --> 15:38.500
Of course, all the new things that are being produced by synthetic morphology and synthetic biology approaches and possible exobiological agents,

15:38.500 --> 15:51.500
because studying just the natural systems that are here on Earth and making conclusions about biology from them is a little bit like testing your theory on the same data set that created it, right?

15:51.500 --> 15:55.500
It's all just an N of one pass through phylogenetic space.

15:55.500 --> 16:07.500
So I tend to think about all kinds of unconventional, different types of embodiments, whether they be evolved, designed, whatever, and really think about this kind of, this is a scale by Rosenbluth, Wiener, and Bigelow.

16:08.500 --> 16:14.500
Looking at all the different kinds of behaviors that one might have in one space. Notice that it says nothing about what it's made of.

16:14.500 --> 16:21.500
It doesn't say anything about having brains or being a specific kind of organism or scale, temporally or whatever. It's all very functional.

16:21.500 --> 16:24.500
So this is how we think about things in my group.

