But first, let's just think about this one particular kind of intelligence, which I think is super interesting, anatomical control as a collective intelligence.

16:42.500 --> 16:54.500
First of all, notice the basic thing that needs explaining, which is that we all start life as a collection of embryonic blastomers, and this is a cross section through a human torso.

16:54.500 --> 17:05.500
So this is what each of us has inside. Now, look at all the incredibly complex invariant order, all the tissues and structures, everything is in the right place next to each other, the right orientation, size, and so on.

17:05.500 --> 17:12.500
So the first question is, where is the shape encoded? How do these cells know to make exactly this?

17:12.500 --> 17:17.500
And you might be tempted to say DNA and genomes, but we can read genomes now.

17:17.500 --> 17:26.500
And what we see is that genomes directly code for protein structure. So the genome specifies the micro level hardware that's present in every cell.

17:26.500 --> 17:34.500
But there's nothing directly that you can read out in the genome about the symmetry type of the organism, the size, the shape, how regenerative it's going to be.

17:34.500 --> 17:39.500
This is very much an open problem of how cells know what to what to make and when to stop.

17:39.500 --> 17:46.500
As workers in regenerative medicine, if parts of this are missing, we'd like to know how to signal the cells to rebuild, to do it again.

17:46.500 --> 17:52.500
And as engineers, we'd like to know, well, what else is possible, right? Given the exact same genome, what else can we ask these cells to do?

17:52.500 --> 17:59.500
Or is this the only thing they could possibly do? And you can sort of visualize forward the end game of this whole field as something like this.

17:59.500 --> 18:07.500
It would be an anatomical compiler where you should be able to sit down and draw at the level of anatomy, the animal or plant that you want.

18:07.500 --> 18:10.500
Not the pathways, not genes, but the actual anatomy.

18:10.500 --> 18:22.500
And if we knew what we were doing, we would have a system that compiled that description into a set of stimuli that would have to be given to cells to get them to build this particular thing.

18:22.500 --> 18:24.500
In this case, a nice three-headed plenarium.

18:24.500 --> 18:28.500
Now, we don't have anything remotely like this. This is a very long term goal.

18:28.500 --> 18:36.500
And the reason that it's really important is because if you think about it, pretty much every problem of biomedicine, with the exception of infectious disease.

18:36.500 --> 18:43.500
So birth defects, traumatic injury, cancer, aging, degenerative disease, all of these things boil down to one problem.

18:43.500 --> 18:47.500
How do you convince cells to build the exact structure that you want?

18:47.500 --> 18:49.500
If we solve that problem, all of this goes away.

18:49.500 --> 18:54.500
We'd be able to fix birth defects, regenerate limbs, reprogram tumors. All of this would go away.

18:54.500 --> 18:58.500
But it's a major problem. Why do we not have an anatomical compiler yet?

18:59.500 --> 19:12.500
So I want to be clear that despite the incredible progress in genetics and molecular biology, we face very fundamental questions that have to do with not with the molecular mechanisms, but with the decision making.

19:12.500 --> 19:14.500
So here's a simple example.

19:14.500 --> 19:16.500
Here is this is a baby axolotl.

