01:03:01.500 --> 01:03:05.500
It folds up right to be back to its to its zen about shape.

01:03:05.500 --> 01:03:11.500
And one of the things we started thinking about is how can we how can we predict what this kind of system is going to do.

01:03:11.500 --> 01:03:13.500
I mean, nobody knew what what they were going to do.

01:03:13.500 --> 01:03:19.500
So so Josh Vanguard lab started modeling their their behavior in this kind of simulation.

01:03:19.500 --> 01:03:26.500
The simulation can actually tell you what the behavior of different shaped bots is going to be and then you can go ahead and microscope them or do various things.

01:03:26.500 --> 01:03:32.500
You can see the patterns that this is just a carmine powder on the bottom of the dish and these guys sweep it along as they go.

01:03:32.500 --> 01:03:35.500
So you can see all the cool patterns that they make as they're navigating.

01:03:35.500 --> 01:03:38.500
But but here's something here's something interesting.

01:03:38.500 --> 01:03:47.500
If you if you simulate them in an environment with a bunch of loose bricks, what you see is that they tend to they tend to collect them into little piles.

01:03:47.500 --> 01:03:49.500
And so what what might be the significance of that?

01:03:49.500 --> 01:03:52.500
Well, it turns out the real bots do exactly that.

01:03:52.500 --> 01:03:58.500
And if you provide them, so these are zenobots provided with a bunch of loose skin cells.

01:03:58.500 --> 01:04:01.500
So these white dots are just loose skin cells hanging around.

01:04:01.500 --> 01:04:05.500
And what you'll see is that these the zenobots will run around.

01:04:05.500 --> 01:04:07.500
They will collect either together or individually.

01:04:07.500 --> 01:04:08.500
They'll make little piles.

01:04:08.500 --> 01:04:13.500
And because this is an agent material, right, these cells are not passive.

01:04:13.500 --> 01:04:16.500
They once the cells are collected into a pile, what do they make?

01:04:16.500 --> 01:04:17.500
They make zenobots.

01:04:17.500 --> 01:04:19.500
So this is kinematic self replication.

01:04:19.500 --> 01:04:23.500
These bots make copies of themselves from the loose material in the dish.

01:04:23.500 --> 01:04:29.500
We've made it impossible for them to replicate the way that normally frogs reproduce.

01:04:29.500 --> 01:04:30.500
So they can't do that.

01:04:30.500 --> 01:04:35.500
But within 48 hours, they show us that there's another way to do this that as far as we know, no other animal uses.

01:04:35.500 --> 01:04:41.500
It's basically Von Neumann's dream, which is machines that will go out and build copies of themselves from parts that they find laying around.

01:04:41.500 --> 01:04:42.500
That's what's going on here.

01:04:42.500 --> 01:04:47.500
These zenobots build the next generation of zenobots out of these loose cells.

01:04:47.500 --> 01:04:50.500
When those mature, I guess what they do, they run around do exactly the same thing.

01:04:50.500 --> 01:04:53.500
You get the next generation and then the next generation after that.

01:04:53.500 --> 01:04:58.500
Now, there's no strong heredity here yet, as far as we know.

01:04:58.500 --> 01:05:01.500
And the reason it works here is really critical.

01:05:01.500 --> 01:05:05.500
The reason it works is the exact same reason that we were able to make zenobots in the first place.

01:05:05.500 --> 01:05:08.500
Because these cells are not passive Legos.

01:05:08.500 --> 01:05:13.500
They are an agent material that once they get together in a particular group, they know what to do.

01:05:13.500 --> 01:05:16.500
They have an innate preference to make bots.

01:05:16.500 --> 01:05:19.500
So that's why these bots are able to make new bots.

01:05:19.500 --> 01:05:25.500
So here's kind of the amazing thing about it is that same genome.

01:05:25.500 --> 01:05:29.500
So if you were to sequence a zenobot, all you would ever see is the Zenopus-Levis genome.

01:05:29.500 --> 01:05:31.500
You'd have no idea that it was any different.

01:05:31.500 --> 01:05:36.500
That same genome can do at least two different life histories.

01:05:36.500 --> 01:05:37.500
It can do this.

01:05:37.500 --> 01:05:43.500
So normal Zenopus stages and then normal tappel behavior.

01:05:43.500 --> 01:05:44.500
Or it can do this.

01:05:44.500 --> 01:05:45.500
Here's an early zenobot.

01:05:45.500 --> 01:05:47.500
Here's a zenobot at about two months.

01:05:47.500 --> 01:05:48.500
It has a developmental sequence.

01:05:48.500 --> 01:05:49.500
It's turning into something.

01:05:49.500 --> 01:05:50.500
What is that?

01:05:50.500 --> 01:05:51.500
I have no idea what that is.

01:05:51.500 --> 01:05:53.500
There's never been any zenobots before.

01:05:53.500 --> 01:05:57.500
So it's some kind of novel developmental stage.

01:05:57.500 --> 01:06:00.500
And eventually they have these kinds of behaviors.

01:06:00.500 --> 01:06:01.500
So we're still working out.

01:06:01.500 --> 01:06:03.500
We don't know how much cognition they actually have.

01:06:03.500 --> 01:06:04.500
Can they learn?

01:06:04.500 --> 01:06:06.500
Can they have preferences?

01:06:06.500 --> 01:06:07.500
What do they react to?

01:06:07.500 --> 01:06:08.500
We don't know.

01:06:08.500 --> 01:06:09.500
We're still figuring that out.

01:06:09.500 --> 01:06:14.500
But the amazing thing about it is that for most animals,

01:06:14.500 --> 01:06:17.500
the way they navigate both physical and anatomical space,

01:06:17.500 --> 01:06:20.500
when you ask why do they have a certain number of legs,

01:06:20.500 --> 01:06:22.500
a certain color, certain behaviors,

01:06:22.500 --> 01:06:23.500
the answer is always,

01:06:23.500 --> 01:06:24.500
well, because for millions of years,

01:06:24.500 --> 01:06:26.500
the ancestors were selected for this or that

01:06:26.500 --> 01:06:28.500
and everybody else died off and now this is what you have.

01:06:28.500 --> 01:06:30.500
Well, there's never been any zenobots.

01:06:30.500 --> 01:06:32.500
And there's never been selection to be a good zenobot.

01:06:32.500 --> 01:06:34.500
All of this is created on the fly.

01:06:34.500 --> 01:06:35.500
This is what they do.

01:06:35.500 --> 01:06:38.500
They create a coherent organism.

01:06:38.500 --> 01:06:42.500
And by the way, if you ask what do skin cells normally want to do,

01:06:42.500 --> 01:06:44.500
you might think that what they normally want to do

01:06:44.500 --> 01:06:47.500
is to be this like passive two-dimensional layer

01:06:47.500 --> 01:06:49.500
on the outside of an animal to keep out the bacteria.

01:06:49.500 --> 01:06:50.500
That isn't what they want to do.

01:06:50.500 --> 01:06:52.500
That's what they're bullied into doing

01:06:52.500 --> 01:06:54.500
by the instructive interactions with the rest of the cells.

01:06:54.500 --> 01:06:55.500
If you don't have those cells,

01:06:55.500 --> 01:06:57.500
this is what they're actually,

01:06:57.500 --> 01:06:59.500
this is actually their default behavior.

01:06:59.500 --> 01:07:02.500
So what evolution does is what bioengineers can

01:07:02.500 --> 01:07:04.500
and will be doing is behavior shaping.

01:07:04.500 --> 01:07:07.500
It's figuring out signals to get your agential material,

01:07:07.500 --> 01:07:09.500
not passive, not a blank slate,

01:07:09.500 --> 01:07:11.500
but your agential material to do whatever you want to do.

